 male actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Orange County, California]]\n[[Category:Male actors from San Diego]]\n[[Category:People from Fountain Valley, California]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toBless This Mess(link changed toBless This Mess (TV series)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ryan_Hansen"}
{"title_page": "Andy Bellatti", "text_new": "{{notability|Biographies|date=April 2016}}\n\n'''Andy Bellatti''' (born May 29, 1982 [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]]) is a [[Las Vegas]]-based [[nutritionist]] who approaches [[nutrition]] from a [[whole food|whole-foods]], plant-centric framework. He also takes a strong interest in [[food politics]], nutrition policy, and [[deceptive marketing|deceptive]] food industry marketing tactics. He also frequently discusses the close relationship between the [[food industry]] and the [[Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics]].<ref name=\"Examine.com.com\" >{{cite web|title=How the food industry spins science to fit its agenda|url=https://examine.com/nutrition/how-the-food-industry-spins-science-to-fit-its-agenda/|work=[[Examine.com]]|accessdate=Apr 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBellatti has contributed to a variety of [[blog]]s and [[website]]s, including \"Mrs. Q\"'s Fed Up With Lunch,<ref>Mrs Q, Fed Up with Lunch, 2011</ref> Vegan.com,<ref name=\"Vegan.com\" >{{cite web|title=Andy Bellatti on Soy vs. Dairy Risk|url=http://vegan.com/blog/2011/07/28/andy-bellatti-on-soy-vs-dairy-risk/|work=Vegan.com|accessdate=July 28, 2011}}</ref> and Robyn Webb's Fabulous Food Finds <ref name=\"Fabulous Food Finds\">{{cite web|last=Webb|first=Robyn|title=Vegetables Make for Wonderful Vessels: Guest post by Andy Bellatti|url=http://www.robynwebb.com/fabulousfoodfinds/?p=1076|work=Fabulous Food Finds|accessdate=August 18, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425064824/http://www.robynwebb.com/fabulousfoodfinds/?p=1076|archive-date=2012-04-25|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n*[http://fedupwithlunch.com/2011/10/guest-blog-post-andy-bellattis-experience-as-a-school-nutritionist/ Andy on Fed Up with Lunch]\n*[http://vegan.com/blog/2011/07/28/andy-bellatti-on-soy-vs-dairy-risk/ Andy on Vegan.com]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120425064824/http://www.robynwebb.com/fabulousfoodfinds/?p=1076 Andy on Robyn Webb's Fabulous Food Finds]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/DietitiansForProfessionalIntegrity Dietitians for Professional Integrity]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*[http://smallbites.andybellatti.com Andy Bellatti's SmallBites Blog]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bellatti, Andy}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Argentine journalists]]\n[[Category:People from Buenos Aires]]\n\n\n{{Argentina-journalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{notability|Biographies|date=April 2016}}\n\n'''Andy Bellatti''' (born May 29, 1982 [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]]) is a [[Las Vegas]]-based [[nutritionist]] who approaches [[nutrition]] from a [[whole food|whole-foods]], plant-centric framework. He also takes a strong interest in [[food politics]], nutrition policy, and [[deceptive marketing|deceptive]] food industry marketing tactics. He also frequently discusses the close relationship between the [[food industry]] and the [[Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics]].<ref name=\"Examine.com.com\" >{{cite web|title=How the food industry spins science to fit its agenda|url=https://examine.com/nutrition/how-the-food-industry-spins-science-to-fit-its-agenda/|work=[[Examine.com]]|accessdate=May 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nBellatti has contributed to a variety of [[blog]]s and [[website]]s, including \"Mrs. Q\"'s Fed Up With Lunch,<ref>Mrs Q, Fed Up with Lunch, 2011</ref> Vegan.com,<ref name=\"Vegan.com\" >{{cite web|title=Andy Bellatti on Soy vs. Dairy Risk|url=http://vegan.com/blog/2011/07/28/andy-bellatti-on-soy-vs-dairy-risk/|work=Vegan.com|accessdate=July 28, 2011}}</ref> and Robyn Webb's Fabulous Food Finds <ref name=\"Fabulous Food Finds\">{{cite web|last=Webb|first=Robyn|title=Vegetables Make for Wonderful Vessels: Guest post by Andy Bellatti|url=http://www.robynwebb.com/fabulousfoodfinds/?p=1076|work=Fabulous Food Finds|accessdate=August 18, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425064824/http://www.robynwebb.com/fabulousfoodfinds/?p=1076|archive-date=2012-04-25|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n*[http://fedupwithlunch.com/2011/10/guest-blog-post-andy-bellattis-experience-as-a-school-nutritionist/ Andy on Fed Up with Lunch]\n*[http://vegan.com/blog/2011/07/28/andy-bellatti-on-soy-vs-dairy-risk/ Andy on Vegan.com]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120425064824/http://www.robynwebb.com/fabulousfoodfinds/?p=1076 Andy on Robyn Webb's Fabulous Food Finds]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/DietitiansForProfessionalIntegrity Dietitians for Professional Integrity]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*[http://smallbites.andybellatti.com Andy Bellatti's SmallBites Blog]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bellatti, Andy}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Argentine journalists]]\n[[Category:People from Buenos Aires]]\n\n\n{{Argentina-journalist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "ScienceandFitness", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andy_Bellatti"}
{"title_page": "Christine Estabrook", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Christine Estabrook\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1952|9|13}}\n| birth_place = \n| years_active = 1979\u2013present\n| spouse      = [[Vic Polizos]] (since 1998)\n| children = 2\n| education = [[State University of New York at Oswego|State University of New York, Oswego]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br/>[[Yale University]] {{small|([[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]])}}\n}}\n'''Christine Estabrook''' <!--(born September 13, 1952)--> is an American actress, known for her roles on the television series ''[[The Crew (TV series)|The Crew]]'', ''[[Nikki (TV series)|Nikki]]'', ''[[Desperate Housewives]]'' and ''[[American Horror Story]]''; she had a recurring role on the drama ''[[Mad Men]]'' during that show's fifth season, and continuing into the sixth and seventh. She has received [[Obie Award]] and [[Drama Desk Award]].<ref>[http://www.ibdb.com/awardperson.asp?id=74054 Christine Estabrook Awards] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125120842/http://ibdb.com/awardperson.asp?id=74054 |date=2010-11-25 }}, [[Internet Broadway Database]]</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\n<!--Estabrook attended the [[Yale School of Drama]] in the 1970s with fellow students [[Wendy Wasserstein]], [[Christopher Durang]], [[Meryl Streep]], and [[Albert Innaurato]], among others.  Known for her comic abilities, she was Lidia in the student production of Durang's ''Titanic'', and played a radical feminist in Durang and Wendy Wasserstein's ''[[When Dinah Shore Ruled the Earth]]''.  At Yale Repertory Theatre she was in Durang-Innaurato's ''[[The Idiots Karamazov]]'', and played [[Hermia]] (opposite Meryl Streep's [[Helena (A Midsummer Night's Dream)|Helena]]) in [[Alvin Epstein]]'s acclaimed production of ''[[A Midsummer Night's Dream]]''.  She also received critical praise for her moving portrayal of a troubled girl in [[Robert Auletta]]'s ''Walk the Dog, Willie'', also at Yale Rep.\n-->\nAt the [[Eugene O'Neill Theater Center#National Playwrights Conference|O'Neill National Playwrights Conference]], she created the role of the young daughter in Kevin O'Morrison's ''Ladyhouse Blues'', which then moved to off-Broadway.  On [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] she was in ''The Inspector General'' and [[Andrei \u0218erban]]'s production of ''The Cherry Orchard''.  She won an [[Obie Award|Obie]] award for her performance in Deborah Eisenberg's ''Pastorale'' at the Second Stage, off-Broadway.  She also created the role of Helen opposite [[William H. Macy]] in Durang's ''Baby with the Bathwater'' at Playwrights Horizons.  And on Broadway she took over the role of Feni in Wendy Wasserstein's ''The Sisters Rosensweig''.  In the fall of 2006, she returned to Broadway in the musical ''[[Spring Awakening (musical)|Spring Awakening]]'' playing all the adult female roles.\n\nSince the 1990s, she has mostly done TV and movies, the latter including include ''Second Sight'', ''Sea of Love'', ''Presumed Innocent'' and ''[[Spider-Man 2]]''.\n\nShe had a recurring role on the popular [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] [[television series]], ''[[Desperate Housewives]]'' playing [[Martha Huber]], the widowed, nosy neighbour of the street and only friend of [[Edie Britt]] ([[Nicollette Sheridan]]). Other appearances include a 2002 episode of the [[HBO]] original series, ''[[Six Feet Under (TV series)|Six Feet Under]]'' where she played Emily Previn, a woman who died alone without any family or friends. The episode sparked much discussion in the following days about the character's death. Estabrook has also guest starred on ''[[7th Heaven (TV series)|7th Heaven]]'', ''[[Dharma and Greg]]'', ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[Veronica Mars]]'' and ''[[NYPD Blue]]''. In 2009 she guest-starred in two episodes of the CBS drama ''[[Ghost Whisperer]]'' as Evelyn James, Eli's mom.\n\nIn 2011 she appeared on the first season of FX series ''[[American Horror Story]]'' (''[[American Horror Story: Murder House|Murder House]]'') as [[Marcy (American Horror Story)|Marcy]]. She later appeared in a recurring role in the [[AMC (TV network)|AMC]] cable television series ''[[Mad Men]]'', playing Joan Harris' mother, Gail Holloway.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[The Bell Jar (film)|The Bell Jar]]''\n| Student editor\n| \n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Pink Floyd \u2013 The Wall|The Wall]]''\n| Rutka\n| \n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[The Lost Honor of Kathryn Beck]]''\n| Janet Reiss\n| Television movie\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Almost You]]''\n| Maggie\n| \n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Sea of Love (film)|Sea of Love]]''\n| Gina Gallagher\n| \n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Second Sight (film)|Second Sight]]''\n| Priscilla Pickett\n| \n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Presumed Innocent (film)|Presumed Innocent]]''\n| Lydia MacDougall\n| \n|-\n| 1991\n| ''One Special Victory''\n| Ruthie\n| Television movie\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[The Usual Suspects]]''\n| Dr. Plummer\n| \n|-\n| 1995\n| ''Kidnapped: In the Line of Duty''\n| {{n/a}}\n| Television movie\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''Special Report: Journey to Mars''\n| {{n/a}}\n| Television movie\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Murder Live!]]''\n| Dr. Christine Winter\n| Television movie\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Chance (2002 film)|Chance]]''\n| Desiree\n| \n|-\n| 2003\n| ''Living in Walter's World''\n| Robin\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Grind (2003 film)|Grind]]''\n| Sarah Jensen\n| \n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Catch That Kid]]''\n| Sharon\n| \n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Spider-Man 2]]''\n| [[Joan Jameson (comics)|Mrs. Jameson]]\n| \n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Lovers, Liars & Lunatics]]''\n| Elaine Rayne\n| \n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Meet Market (film)|Meet Marker]]''\n| Mom\n| \n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Backyard Wedding]]''\n| Joanne Blake\n| Television movie\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Is That a Gun in Your Pocket?]]''\n| Shirley Parsons\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\